result.execSummary:
The defendant Cynthia Caldwell was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Maintain Drug Trafficking Place [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.42(1).
  • Possess w/Intent-Cocaine (>15-40g) [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class D felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(cm)3.

Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. Defendant Cynthia Caldwell in court with attorney Edward Lee Wright.  Defendant Cynthia Caldwell in custody.  Megan M. Williamson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Sentencing proceeded.  PSI reviewed.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Additional statements by: Mother, Betty R.

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 2 YEARS, CONCURRENT TO COUNT 2, and CONSECUTIVE with any other sentence, with credit for 71 DAYS time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 1 YEAR.  The defendant IS NOT ELIGIBLE for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program and IS NOT ELIGIBLE for the Challenge Incarceration Program. 

AS TO COUNT 2:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 4 YEARS, CONCURRENT TO COUNT 1, and CONSECUTIVE with any other sentence, with credit for 71 DAYS time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  The defendant IS NOT ELIGIBLE for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program and IS NOT ELIGIBLE for the Challenge Incarceration Program. 

AS TO BOTH COUNTS:
The Court imposed the following conditions of extended supervision:  

- Maintain absolute sobriety, no controlled substances without a valid prescription, with random drug tests.
- Maintain full time employment, school, or a combination of both.
- No contact with Joshua S., in person or thru a third party.
- No association with known drug users or dealers, and no contact at any place where illegal drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged, or distributed.
- Complete a cognitive restructuring intervention program.
- Do not possess or use any dangerous weapon.
- Comply with any treatment or programs recommeded by agent, which may include a parenting class and or educational training.
- Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample, and to pay all MANDATORY COURT costs, fees, assessments, and surcharges through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Defendant to make regular monthly payments.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.
- Pay all supervision fees.  Defendant to make regular payments.

Defendant is remanded.

Court ordered that the defendant cannot vote until civil rights are restored upon completion of sentence.
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon that he may never possess a firearm.
Court advised defendant of his right to seek postconviction relief.
